equation_narrative.headline: Hydrophobic core context drives L/I/F competition, leucine wins late
equation_narrative.story: Position 13 in ubiquitin sits in a hydrophobic core with 4 structural contacts. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation consistent with buried, branched-chain hydrophobic residues—the logit lens shows V, A, and T leading early, reflecting the compact, aliphatic character of the local environment. The decision phase (L24-33) sees intense competition among large hydrophobics: I surges to 53% at L31 via strong MLP support, but L overtakes it in the final two layers through attention-driven features. The model predicts leucine (45%) over the correct isoleucine (20%), with phenylalanine (23%) as a strong runner-up, reflecting the model's read of the position as tolerating bulky hydrophobic side chains.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather structural and chemical context. Four structural contacts provide hydrophobic signal—attention heads at L12 and L20 read these neighbors, with L20:H0 contributing +1.51 projection without clear sourcing (likely integrating distributed hydrophobic features). Early SAE features (F1:5480, F1:9146, both 45+ proj) encode position identity and local sequence. By mid-layers, the representation shifts from small aliphatics (A, V dominate L5-L19 in logit lens, peaking at 28% for V at L17) toward larger hydrophobics. L18 MLP neurons strongly support I (+1.86 total projection), with N18:4563 casting +0.33 for I. Co-evolutionary signal is minimal (only 2 co-evolving positions), so the decision relies primarily on local structural chemistry.
perception_phase.context_character: Buried hydrophobic core environment with compact, branched-chain aliphatic character. Structural contacts favor medium-to-large hydrophobic residues (V, I, L), with no polar or charged constraints evident.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 4 residues within contact distance, predominantly hydrophobic—read by L20:H0 (+1.51 proj) and L27:H15 (+1.33 proj, 96% structural attention)
Co-evolutionary signal: minimal (2 positions), insufficient to constrain the decision
L18 MLP: strong I-writing neurons (N18:4563 +0.33, N18:2169 +0.29) establish hydrophobic preference
L16 MLP: N16:3167 (+0.31 for I) and N16:4463 (+0.23 for I) reinforce branched-chain aliphatic character

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes in layers 27-33 with fierce competition among L, I, and F. I dominates at L31 (53%, driven by MLP neurons N31:2949 +0.49 and N31:858 +0.44), but L surges in the final layers via attention mechanisms—L31:H13 writes +2.25 with 96% local attention, and L32:H18 adds +1.75 with structural focus. F remains a strong contender throughout (peaks 24% at L28), supported by aromatic-tolerant features. The final output (L 45%, F 23%, I 20%) reflects the model's assessment that the position tolerates bulky hydrophobics, with L winning on late-stage local sequence integration.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-25, the representation shifts from encoding hydrophobic context to activating amino-acid-specific prediction channels. L24 SAE features (F24:798, F24:5827, both 11-14 proj) mark the first appearance of decision-level features. MLP activity at L24 shows mixed signals (total projection -0.85), but by L25 the competition among L/I/F is fully engaged, with V dropping from 27% to 7% as the model commits to larger hydrophobics.

candidates.narrative: Leucine emerges as a serious contender only in late layers, rising from 9% at L23 to 45% at L33. The decisive push comes from attention mechanisms at L31-33: L31:H13 contributes +2.25 (96% local attention), and L32:H18 adds +1.75 (13% structural attention). L33 SAE features (F33:4166, F33:1345, both 90+ proj) represent strong L-specific prediction channels. MLP support is modest but consistent in late layers (N29:1322 +0.68 for I but also supports L).
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L29 (27%), surges L31-33 to win at 45%
key_evidence: L31:H13 (attn, +2.25 proj) — local sequence writer, 96% local attention
L32:H18 (attn, +1.75 proj) — structural writer integrating contact chemistry

candidates.narrative: Phenylalanine maintains steady support from L24 onward, peaking at 24% at L28. It benefits from the model's read of the position as tolerating bulky, hydrophobic residues. F-specific features appear in late layers (F30:3674 with 56.9 proj likely supports aromatic character), and MLP neurons at L28-29 provide modest support. F never leads but remains competitive throughout the decision phase, finishing at 23%.
candidates.key_layers: Steady from L24 (1.7%) through L33 (23%), peaks L28 (24%)
key_evidence: L28 MLP: mixed signals but F-compatible neurons active
Consistent 17-24% probability L28-33 indicates stable aromatic-compatible representation

candidates.narrative: Isoleucine is the correct answer but finishes third at 20%. It dominates the mid-to-late decision phase, surging from 12% at L23 to 53% at L31—the highest probability any candidate achieves. Strong MLP support drives this peak: N31:2949 (+0.49), N31:858 (+0.44), and earlier N21:1313 (+0.49) all favor I. However, I loses ground in the final two layers as attention mechanisms at L31-33 redirect support toward L. The model's failure to sustain I reflects over-reliance on late-stage local sequence features that favor L.
key_evidence: N31:2949 (MLP, +0.49 for I) — strong I-specific neuron
N21:1313 (MLP, +0.49 for I) — early I support
L31 peak at 53% shows I was briefly the model's top choice

candidates.narrative: Valine leads the logit lens from L13 to L26, peaking at 29% at L27. This reflects the representation's character through the perception phase: V is consistent with compact, branched-chain aliphatic residues in buried environments. However, V is not a prediction—it's a projection artifact of the hydrophobic context being assembled. As the model transitions to decision-making, V collapses (7% at L29, 4% at L33) because the position's structural contacts favor larger hydrophobics (L, I, F).
candidates.key_layers: Leads L13-L26, peaks L27 (29%), collapses L29+ to 4%
key_evidence: L17 logit lens: V at 17%, consistent with compact aliphatic representation
L27 peak (29%) coincides with final perception-phase integration
Collapse at L29 (-20 percentage points) marks decision-phase rejection of smaller hydrophobics

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from small aliphatics (A, V) toward larger hydrophobics (I, L, F). L16 MLP neurons (N16:3167 +0.31, N16:4463 +0.23) strongly support I, contributing +1.22 total projection. L18 MLP adds +1.86, with N18:4563 (+0.33 for I) and N18:2169 (+0.29 for I) reinforcing the branched-chain preference. Attention at L16 (total delta +2.42) integrates structural contacts, solidifying the hydrophobic core character.

Isoleucine surges to dominance, rising from 11% at L23 to 53% at L31. This is driven by MLP neurons at L27-31: N27:4150 (+0.52), N29:1322 (+0.68), N31:2949 (+0.49), and N31:858 (+0.44) all favor I. L27:H15 (structural writer, +1.33) and L31:H13 (local writer, +2.25) provide attention support. At L31, I briefly becomes the model's top choice, but this peak is unstable—L and F remain competitive.

Leucine overtakes isoleucine in the final two layers. L31:H13 writes +2.25 for I initially, but L32:H18 (+1.75, structural focus) and L32:H13 (+1.39, co-evolutionary focus) redirect support toward L. L33 MLP contributes +3.6 (velocity event), with final SAE features (F33:4166, F33:1345, both 90+ proj) activating L-specific prediction channels. I collapses from 53% to 20%, while L rises from 35% to 45%. This late reversal reflects the model's final integration of local sequence context favoring L over I.

deep_dives.label: Structural attention L12-L20
deep_dives.caption: L12:H1 erases (-1.90 proj) without clear sourcing, possibly suppressing polar alternatives. L20:H0 writes +1.51 for I, integrating distributed hydrophobic features from structural neighbors. These heads establish the buried, hydrophobic character that dominates the perception phase.

deep_dives.label: MLP I-writing L16-L19
deep_dives.caption: L16 and L18 MLPs provide the strongest early support for isoleucine. N16:3167 (+0.31), N16:4463 (+0.23), N18:4563 (+0.33), and N18:2169 (+0.29) all favor I, establishing it as the leading large hydrophobic by L19. This sets up I's dominance in the mid-decision phase.

deep_dives.label: Decision onset L24 SAE features
deep_dives.caption: L24 marks the transition from perception to decision. F24:798 (13.6 proj), F24:5827 (12.1 proj), and F24:5039 (11.9 proj) are the first amino-acid-specific prediction channels to activate. These features shift the representation from 'hydrophobic context' to 'candidate amino acids.'

deep_dives.label: MLP I-surge L29-L31
deep_dives.caption: Isoleucine's peak at L31 (53%) is driven by these MLP layers. N29:1322 (+0.68), N31:2949 (+0.49), and N31:858 (+0.44) all cast strong votes for I. However, L30 MLP has negative total projection (-4.56), indicating competing erasure signals that destabilize I's lead.

deep_dives.label: Attention L31-L33 L-writers
deep_dives.caption: Leucine's late victory is driven by attention mechanisms. L31:H13 (+2.25, 96% local attention) and L32:H18 (+1.75, 13% structural attention) redirect support from I to L. L32:H13 (+1.39, 29% co-evolutionary attention) adds co-evolutionary signal, though only 2 co-evolving positions exist.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction channels L33
deep_dives.caption: L33 SAE features represent the model's final prediction channels. F33:4166 (92.8 proj), F33:1345 (92.1 proj), and F33:9048 (91.1 proj) are all L-specific features with very high projections. These features encode the model's final commitment to leucine over isoleucine.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly identifies position 13 as a buried hydrophobic core site requiring a large, branched-chain aliphatic residue. Through layers 1-23, it assembles a representation consistent with compact hydrophobics (V, A), then shifts to larger candidates (L, I, F) in the decision phase. Isoleucine briefly dominates (53% at L31) via strong MLP support, but leucine wins through late-stage attention mechanisms (L31:H13, L32:H18) that integrate local sequence context. The model's error—predicting L over the correct I—stems from over-weighting local sequence features in the final layers, which favor L's slightly different side-chain geometry. The 45% vs 20% margin suggests the model views L and I as nearly interchangeable in this context, a reasonable biochemical assessment given their structural similarity.
